 quiet intensity and "idian practices of refusal. Originally intended to dehumanize, police, and restrict their subjects, these photographs convey the softly buzzing tension of colonialism, the low hum of resistance and subversion, and the anticipation and performance of a future that has yet to happen. Engaging with discourses of fugitivity, black futurity, and black feminist theory, Campt takes these tools of colonialism and repurposes them, hearing and sharing their moments of refusal, rupture, and imagination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aAfricansxPortraits. 0aBlacksxPortraits. 0aIdentification photographs. 0aPortrait photographyxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPortrait photographyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPhotography / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822373582zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822373582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822373582.jpg  a978-3-11-069634-9  DUK eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles